Thank you.

00:00:04.013 --> 00:00:10.484
So, my father used to always tell me something
which I want to share with you, that why do

00:00:10.484 --> 00:00:13.634
you want to fit inside a glass slipper?

00:00:13.634 --> 00:00:18.394
You know, like we were told, like Cinderella
did, why do you want to fit inside a glass

00:00:18.394 --> 00:00:22.754
slipper when you can shatter the glass ceiling?

00:00:22.754 --> 00:00:25.233
I want to tell you a little secret.

00:00:25.233 --> 00:00:30.004
I'm not very fond of this phrase, breaking
the glass ceiling.

00:00:30.004 --> 00:00:31.274
Why does it annoy me?

00:00:31.274 --> 00:00:34.973
Because it takes the context of everything
that I have done.

00:00:34.973 --> 00:00:41.884
All my achievements, all my hard work and
puts it into a box as if my ambition was that

00:00:41.884 --> 00:00:43.943
I want to find a glass ceiling and break it.

00:00:43.943 --> 00:00:45.304
Not at all.

00:00:45.304 --> 00:00:50.854
To be really honest, I was never on a mission
to break, to shatter anything.

00:00:50.854 --> 00:00:56.154
All I wanted was to chase my dreams, my ambitions.

00:00:56.154 --> 00:00:57.524
I wanted to evolve.

00:00:57.524 --> 00:01:02.264
I wanted to become the best version of me,
that I could be.

00:01:02.264 --> 00:01:05.804
And of course, in Priyanka Chopra style, along
the way, I wanted to smash and break every

00:01:05.804 --> 00:01:09.973
obstacle that came my way, which I did.

00:01:09.973 --> 00:01:12.973
But that does not mean that the glass ceiling
doesn't exist.

00:01:12.973 --> 00:01:14.973
Of course, it exists.

00:01:14.973 --> 00:01:21.073
And countless of women and men, mostly women
run into it in their professional and personal

00:01:21.073 --> 00:01:22.073
lives.

00:01:22.073 --> 00:01:25.694
And I'm sure a lot of you can vouch for that
right now.

00:01:25.694 --> 00:01:33.603
The Oxford dictionary definition of the glass
ceiling is an unacknowledged barrier to advancement

00:01:33.603 --> 00:01:40.944
in a profession, especially affecting women
and members of minorities from rising beyond

00:01:40.944 --> 00:01:43.933
a certain level in a hierarchy.

00:01:43.933 --> 00:01:48.944
And this metaphor was first coined by feminists
in reference to barriers in the careers of

00:01:48.944 --> 00:01:51.323
high achieving women.

00:01:51.323 --> 00:01:57.904
So, why did I choose it as my topic for today
if I hated it so much?

00:01:57.904 --> 00:02:04.624
Because I hope through my experiences, I can
present to you the tools to live your dream

00:02:04.624 --> 00:02:12.144
and to not make that glass ceiling that is
defined by society, largely patriarchal, as

00:02:12.144 --> 00:02:13.953
your goal.

00:02:13.953 --> 00:02:20.703
I want you to aim higher, because you know
you can, and it's honestly all I did.

00:02:20.703 --> 00:02:24.854
Every step of the way, all I did was set a
higher standard.

00:02:24.854 --> 00:02:26.604
How did I get here?

00:02:26.604 --> 00:02:36.754
By being fierce, by being fearless, and by
being flawed, completely and utterly flawed.

00:02:36.754 --> 00:02:38.254
I'm not perfect.

00:02:38.254 --> 00:02:39.664
Like, none of us are.

00:02:39.664 --> 00:02:43.924
So, tonight I'm going to try and break it
down for you a little bit in a slightly different

00:02:43.924 --> 00:02:44.924
way.

00:02:44.924 --> 00:02:50.823
I present the twelve sure shot, sure fireways
of becoming Priyanka Chopra.

00:02:50.823 --> 00:02:52.044
Would you like that?

00:02:52.044 --> 00:02:55.763
Sorry, I was just kidding.

00:02:55.763 --> 00:02:59.123
Because as millennials, we don't like to be
told what to do.

00:02:59.123 --> 00:03:03.004
So, this is a gentle nudge in the right direction.

00:03:03.004 --> 00:03:07.343
Presenting PCs twelve rules of becoming the
best version of yourself.

00:03:07.343 --> 00:03:10.934
So, here are a few of my favorites from my
list.

00:03:10.934 --> 00:03:15.334
There's only one you, okay, because there's
no one like you.

00:03:15.334 --> 00:03:19.254
And I don't mean the superfluous, superficial
parts.

00:03:19.254 --> 00:03:21.994
I'm talking about the core of you, who you
are inside.

00:03:21.994 --> 00:03:24.573
Your values, your beliefs, your flaws.

00:03:24.573 --> 00:03:31.584
And once you understand who really that person
is, you would have taken the first step in

00:03:31.584 --> 00:03:33.513
finding your unique self.

00:03:33.513 --> 00:03:34.843
And that is the best version of you.

00:03:34.843 --> 00:03:37.153
Who am I really?

00:03:37.153 --> 00:03:41.823
Most often, we don't allow ourselves the ability
to dream beyond our imagination.

00:03:41.823 --> 00:03:46.184
We don't allow ourselves to think about the
future because we are afraid of change.

00:03:46.184 --> 00:03:49.154
We are afraid to move away from what is familiar.

00:03:49.154 --> 00:03:54.203
Either that, or sometimes, you know, we are
too rigid to let our dreams evolve.

00:03:54.203 --> 00:03:58.823
Loosen up, you know, shake it off a little
bit.

00:03:58.823 --> 00:04:04.114
Change is the only constant thing in life,
and you are never too old or never too experienced

